    <body>
        <div xml:id="KT124-kilavi">
          <p type="edition">puṇarntuṭaṉ pōkkiṉait talaimakaḷ oḻiyap pōkaluṟṟat talaimakaṟkut tōḻi colliyatu.</p>
          <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">Uttered by the confidante to HIM, who undertook to go while SHE would stay behind, about unitedly going away together.</p>
          </div>


        <div xml:id="KT124">
            <lg type="edition">
<l>                umaṇar cērntu kaḻinta maruṅki ṉakaṉṟalai</l>
<l>                yūrpāḻt taṉṉa vōmaiyam peruṅkā</l>
<l>                ṭiṉṉā veṉṟi rāyi</l>
<l>                ṉiṉiyavō peruma tamiyōrkku maṉaiyē.</l>
             </lg>
            <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
           <l>If, [as] you would say,</l>
           <l rend="indent3">[it is] unsweet,</l>
           <l rend="indent">the big wilderness of Ōmai trees, like a ruined village</l>
           <l rend="indent">in the open<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">maruṅkiṉ akaṉṟalai</term>: What is achieved by this hypermetrical redundancy? Srin. proposes to connect the latter with the <term xml:lang="ta">ūr</term> of the next line: something like "important place" ("main-<term xml:lang="ta">ūr</term>" + <term xml:lang="ta">akaṉ</term> "broad" in the sense of "wide" or, figuratively, "important").</note>, the side of which all<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">cērntu</term> seems to be used to denote the whole of the salt merchants, that is, the salt merchants travelling in a group (thus TVG).</note> the salt merchants<note place="foot">The cultural impact of this image is not clear and we are missing the sociological background. TVG gives a nice interpretation, namely that the group of travelling salt merchants (on their way to sell their salt across the country) just take rest in this deserted place and then move on. Now semantically <term xml:lang="ta">kaḻinta</term> rather seems to mean "to pass by", that is, without even taking a short halt, but that might be just a stronger version of the same interpretation: the village is so run down that it is not even considered as a resting place.</note> passed by</l>
           <l>– are the houses sweet, o great one, for those left alone?</l>
            </lg>
        </div>
